PURPOSE:
==========================================================================================

Nargs provides a non-intrusive generative framework to incept the Python-feature
of named arguments to callable objects in C++.

Nargs can be used to generate new interfaces, but it can also serve as a tool
for non-intrusive improvement of the safety and readability of existing interfaces.


INSTRUCTIONS:
==========================================================================================


1. Read doc/README for a general introduction with two examples

2. Read doc/signatures.txt and doc/nargs.txt for a detailed API-documentation

3. Study the examples in examples

4. Note the compilation instructions below in this file (COMPILATION INSTRUCTIONS).

The order of (2) and (3) is not fixed. It is possible to study the examples directly while
consulting the reference documentation in doc/signatures.txt and doc/nargs.txt when
needed.


COMPILATION:
==========================================================================================
Nargs is a header-only library. It suffices to include either the header nargs/nargs.hpp
or nargs/signature.hpp. The header nargs.hpp include everything, whereas the header
signatrues.hpp includes everything except the macro NARG_PAIR. Users are not required to
use the macro NARG_PAIR.

C++17 prerequisite: Nargs uses the C++17-function std::invoke. Hence it is necessary to
enable C++17 support via the appropriate compiler flags (-std=c++1z for gcc/clang).


DOCUMENTATION:
==========================================================================================
Given in the following files:

doc/README
doc/nargs.hpp.txt
doc/signatures.hpp.txt


EXAMPLES:
==========================================================================================

Given in the directory examples.


